The heat–Liouville commutator admits a small-\(\varepsilon\) expansion that isolates the leading piece and quantifies the remainder:

\[
\bigl[e^{\varepsilon\Delta},\mathcal L\bigr]\rho(s)
   \;=\;
   \varepsilon\,\underbrace{[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(s)}_{\text{first–order}}
   \;+\;
   \mathcal R_{2}(\varepsilon,s),
\tag{1}
\]

where the remainder satisfies a uniform bound of the form  

\[
\|\mathcal R_{2}(\varepsilon,s)\|_{\infty}
   \;\le\;
   C\,\varepsilon^{2}\,
   \bigl(\|\nabla^{4}\rho(s)\|_{\infty}
         +\|\nabla^{3}\rho(s)\|_{\infty}\bigr),
\qquad 0<\varepsilon\le1,
\tag{2}
\]

for some constant \(C\) depending only on finitely many derivatives of the smooth vector field \(v\).

Consequently, the commutator contribution inside the integrand is

\[
\partial_\varepsilon\!\left(
   \frac{\bigl[e^{\varepsilon\Delta},\mathcal L\bigr]\rho(s)}{\rho_\varepsilon}
\right)
\;=\;
\partial_\varepsilon\!\left(
   \frac{\varepsilon\,[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(s)}{\rho_\varepsilon}
\right)
\;+\;
\partial_\varepsilon\!\left(
   \frac{\mathcal R_{2}(\varepsilon,s)}{\rho_\varepsilon}
\right),
\tag{3}
\]

where the first term is \(O(\varepsilon^{-1})\) after differentiation (it inherits one explicit \(\varepsilon\)), and the second term is \(O(\varepsilon)\) by (2) and smoothness of \(\rho_\varepsilon\).  This cleanly separates the dominant first-order part \(\varepsilon[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(s)\) from an error that is \(O(\varepsilon)\) relative to it.

(Stop here.)

Putting everything we have so far **back under the time–integral** (and still ignoring the \(O(\varepsilon^2)\) remainder we set aside):

\[
\boxed{
\begin{aligned}
&\varepsilon
\Bigl(
      \partial_\varepsilon\!\log\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)
      -\partial_\varepsilon\!\log\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)
\Bigr)
\\
&\qquad
=\;
\varepsilon\!
\int_{t(\varepsilon)}^{\infty}
      \Bigl[
            v(x)\!\cdot\!\nabla\!\Bigl(\frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon}{\rho_\varepsilon}\Bigr)(x,s)
            \;-\;
            \frac{[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(s)}{\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}
            \;+\;
            \varepsilon\,
            \frac{[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(s)\,\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}
                 {\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)^{2}}
      \Bigr]\,
      ds .
\end{aligned}}
\tag{\(\star\)}
\]

* **First term** in the brackets comes from  
  \(\partial_\varepsilon\!\bigl[-v\!\cdot\nabla\log\rho_\varepsilon\bigr]
      =-v\!\cdot\nabla\!\bigl(\Delta\rho_\varepsilon/\rho_\varepsilon\bigr)\).

* **Second and third terms** come from  
  \(\partial_\varepsilon\!\bigl[\varepsilon[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(s)/\rho_\varepsilon\bigr]
      =[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(s)/\rho_\varepsilon
        -\varepsilon[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(s)\,\Delta\rho_\varepsilon/\rho_\varepsilon^{2}\).

Everything inside the integral is now explicit; the next step (not done here) would be to estimate each bracketed piece and choose \(t(\varepsilon)\) so that the whole integral vanishes as \(\varepsilon\to0\).

this term is very ugly is it possible to get rid of it but selecting a trajectory x(t). The problem I see with this is that the \rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty) term can't be expressed in terms of an x trajectory because x evolves forever. How can we change our initial expression to make sure this problematic term doesn't appear:

$$
\boxed{\;
\lim_{\varepsilon\to0}\;
\varepsilon\Bigl(
      \frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}%
           {\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}
      -\frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}%
           {\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}
\Bigr)=0\;}.
\tag{1}
$$

**Trick: evaluate both curvatures at the *same* moving point  
\(x(t)=\Phi_{t}(x_{0})\).**

Because the flow is divergence-free, the limiting density \(\rho_{\infty}\) satisfies \(\rho_{\infty}\!\circ\!\Phi_{t}=\rho_{\infty}\).  Hence

\[
\frac{\Delta\rho_{\varepsilon}(x(t),\infty)}{\rho_{\varepsilon}(x(t),\infty)}
      =\frac{\Delta\rho_{\varepsilon}(x_{0},\infty)}{\rho_{\varepsilon}(x_{0},\infty)}
      \quad\text{for every }t.
\]

So we can target

\[
\boxed{\;
\lim_{\varepsilon\to0}\;
\varepsilon\Bigl(
      \frac{\Delta\rho_{\varepsilon}\bigl(x(t(\varepsilon)),t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}
           {\rho_{\varepsilon}\bigl(x(t(\varepsilon)),t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}
      -\frac{\Delta\rho_{\varepsilon}(x_{0},\infty)}
           {\rho_{\varepsilon}(x_{0},\infty)}
\Bigr)=0.
\;}\tag{1'}
\]

---

### Why (1′) removes the ugly advection term

Apply the material derivative \(D/Dt=\partial_{t}+v\!\cdot\nabla\):

\[
\frac{D}{Dt}\Bigl[\varepsilon\partial_{\varepsilon}\log\rho_{\varepsilon}\bigr(x(t),t\bigl)\Bigr]
    =\varepsilon\,\partial_{\varepsilon}
       \!\left[\frac{e^{\varepsilon\Delta}[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(t)}
                     {\rho_{\varepsilon}}\right]_{x=x(t)} ,
\]

so the troublesome piece \(v\!\cdot\nabla(\Delta\rho_{\varepsilon}/\rho_{\varepsilon})\) never appears—the material derivative already contains it.  Integrating from \(0\) to \(t(\varepsilon)\) gives

\[
\varepsilon\frac{\Delta\rho_{\varepsilon}}{\rho_{\varepsilon}}
         \bigl(x(t(\varepsilon)),t(\varepsilon)\bigr)
     -\varepsilon\frac{\Delta\rho_{\varepsilon}}{\rho_{\varepsilon}}(x_{0},0)
    \;=\;
    \varepsilon\!\int_{0}^{t(\varepsilon)}
        \partial_{\varepsilon}
        \!\left[\frac{e^{\varepsilon\Delta}[\Delta,\mathcal L]\rho(s)}
                       {\rho_{\varepsilon}}\right]_{x=x(s)}ds .
\]

Replace the harmless \(O(\varepsilon)\) initial value by the constant
\(\varepsilon\frac{\Delta\rho_{\varepsilon}}{\rho_{\varepsilon}}(x_{0},\infty)\)
to recover (1′).  
The integrand is now *only* the heat–Liouville commutator (plus the familiar \(O(\varepsilon)\) remainder), so the same scaling choice  
\(e^{2\lambda_{\max}t(\varepsilon)}=o(1/\varepsilon)\) forces the whole integral to \(0\).

Thus (1′) keeps the reference to the limit density, kills the advection term, and needs no new auxiliary symbols.

After the cancellations you just identified, the integrand that remains under the time-integral is the **pure commutator remainder**:

\[
\partial_s\partial_\varepsilon\log\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)\;=\;
\frac{e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\bigl[\Delta,\mathcal L\bigr]\rho(s)}
     {\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}
\;-\;
\frac{\bigl[e^{\varepsilon\Delta},\mathcal L\bigr]\rho(s)}
     {\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}
     \,\frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}{\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}.
\]

Hence the quantity we are driving to zero is

\[
-\;\varepsilon\int_{\,t(\varepsilon)}^{\infty}\!
\Biggl[
   \frac{e^{\varepsilon\Delta}\bigl[\Delta,\mathcal L\bigr]\rho(s)}
        {\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}
   \;-\;
   \frac{\bigl[e^{\varepsilon\Delta},\mathcal L\bigr]\rho(s)}
        {\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}
        \,\frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}{\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}
\Biggr]ds.
\]

No advection term survives; only the genuine commutator pieces appear inside the full time integral.

**Set-up (no new symbols introduced)**  

Start with the quantity whose \(\varepsilon\!\to\!0\) limit we want to drive to zero:

\[
\varepsilon\Bigl(
      \frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}%
           {\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}
      \;-\;
      \frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}%
           {\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}
\Bigr).
\tag{1}
\]

Write the difference of Laplacians as an **integral in time** (fundamental theorem of calculus):

\[
\Delta\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)-\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)
\;=\;
-\!\int_{\,t(\varepsilon)}^{\infty}
      \partial_s\bigl[\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)\bigr]\,ds.
\tag{2}
\]

Insert (2) into (1) *without* introducing extra shorthand:

\[
\varepsilon\Bigl(
      \frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}%
           {\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}
      -\frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}%
           {\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}
\Bigr)
=
-\;
\frac{\varepsilon}{\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}
\int_{\,t(\varepsilon)}^{\infty}
      \partial_s\bigl[\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)\bigr]\,ds
+
\varepsilon\,\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)
\Bigl(
      \frac{1}{\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}
      -\frac{1}{\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}
\Bigr).
\tag{3}
\]

All that remains is to estimate the two pieces of (3); doing so will pin down how fast \(t(\varepsilon)\) must grow relative to \(|\log\varepsilon|\) to make the whole expression vanish.

**Goal.**  
Show  
\[
\varepsilon\Bigl(
      \frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}%
           {\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}
      \;-\;
      \frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}%
           {\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}
\Bigr)\;\xrightarrow{\;\varepsilon\to0\;}0.
\tag{1}
\]

---

### Put the difference into an integral—keep the fractions intact  

For every fixed \(\varepsilon>0\) the map \(s\mapsto\displaystyle
\frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}{\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}\) is smooth in \(s\).  
Hence, using the fundamental theorem of calculus *without splitting numerators and denominators*:

\[
\frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}%
     {\rho_\varepsilon\bigl(x,t(\varepsilon)\bigr)}
-
\frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}%
     {\rho_\varepsilon(x,\infty)}
\;=\;
-\int_{\,t(\varepsilon)}^{\infty}
      \partial_s\!\left(
            \frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}{\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}
      \right)\,ds.
\tag{2}
\]

Insert (2) directly into (1):

\[
\boxed{
\;
\varepsilon
\int_{\,t(\varepsilon)}^{\infty}
      \Biggl|
      \partial_s\!\left(
            \frac{\Delta\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}{\rho_\varepsilon(x,s)}
      \right)
      \Biggr|\,ds
\;\xrightarrow{\;\varepsilon\to0\;}0\;
}.
\]

---

Everything that remains is to estimate the integrand  
\(\displaystyle\partial_s\!\bigl[\Delta\rho_\varepsilon/\rho_\varepsilon\bigr]\)  
and choose a schedule \(t(\varepsilon)\) that makes the integral vanish.  No further algebraic breakup of the fractions is needed for the rest of the proof.

