Not quite.  The Hessian of \(\log f\) contains an extra quadratic-gradient term.

\[
\nabla^2\!\log f
\;=\;
\nabla\!\Bigl(\frac{\nabla f}{f}\Bigr)
\;=\;
\frac{\nabla^2 f}{f}\;-\;\frac{\nabla f\;\otimes\;\nabla f}{f^{\,2}}.
\]

So  

\[
\boxed{\;
\nabla^2\!\log f
\;=\;
\frac{\nabla^2 f}{f}\;-\;\frac{\nabla f\,\nabla f^{\!\top}}{f^{2}}
\;}
\]

and the simple quotient \(\tfrac{\nabla^2 f}{f}\) equals \(\nabla^2\!\log f\) only in special cases (e.g.\ when \(\nabla f=0\) at the point, or more generally when \(\nabla f\) is negligibly small compared with \(f\)).

Let \(T\) be any rank-two (second-order) tensor.   Using  

\[
\frac{\nabla^{2}f}{f}
=\nabla^{2}\!\log f \;+\;(\nabla\log f)\otimes(\nabla\log f),
\]

contract term-by-term:

\[
T:\frac{\nabla^{2}f}{f}
\;=\;
T:\nabla^{2}\!\log f
\;+\;
T:\!\bigl[(\nabla\log f)\otimes(\nabla\log f)\bigr].
\]

Because \(T:(v\otimes v)=v^{\!\top}T\,v\), the second piece can be written more compactly as a quadratic form:

\[
T:\frac{\nabla^{2}f}{f}
\;=\;
T:\nabla^{2}\!\log f
\;+\;
(\nabla\log f)^{\!\top}T\,\nabla\log f.
\]

Either of these two equivalent expressions cleanly captures the double-dot contraction in purely logarithmic terms.
